<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-441-249  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 441 249.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  August 14 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Products shown offsite during MacWorld Expo.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>McMullen, Barbare E.; McMullen, John F.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (public relations)Timeworks Inc. (public relations).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Product:   DataClub (Computer network software) (advertising).andO;Topic:     MacWorld ExpositionNew ProductData base management systemsNetwork Software.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>PRODUCTS SHOWN OFFSITE DURING MACWORLD EXPO BOSTON, MASSACHUSETTS, U.S.A.,andO;1990 AUG 14 (NB) -- International Business Software provided private showingsof its DataClub networking product to press and representatives of largecorporations at Boston's Ritz-Carleton hotel during the recent MacWorldExpo/Boston.andP;  IBS did not exhibit at MacWorld but choose rather toconcentrate on this direct meeting with interested parties in a quieteratmosphere with less distraction.andM;Eric Gould, IBS vice president of marketing, told Newsbytes: &quot;The use of asuite at the Ritz-Carleton was as expensive as exhibiting at the show wouldhave been.andP;  It was not a matter of cost that caused us to choose this methodof display.andP;  It was, rather, an attempt to receive more for our investment.andO;DataClub represents a new concept of networking and it's difficult to be ableto properly explain that in a more hectic environment.andP;  We wanted to be ableto present the system in a manner that persons might be able to more properlyappreciate the power of this unique product.&quot;andM;DataClub is a networking system which spreads data files over the resourcesin the system.andP;  Gould explains that by using all of the available computersin the system as file servers, &quot;the system performance actually improves asthe system gets larger.andP;  In all other approaches, there is degradation inperformance as users are added to the system.&quot;andM;Although DataClub utilizes all networked machines to store networked files,the physical location of the files is transparent to users and is shown aspart of the logical volume DataClub.andP;  The product is compatible and compliantwith AFP (AppleTalk Filing Protocol).andP;  It will ship in September and retailfor $295 for 3 users and $795 for 10 users.andM;Another Macintosh product provider, Timeworks, Inc., also chose a non-exhibit approach during MacWorld and used a trailer parked in the BaysideExposition parking lot to hold private discussions with press and preliminaryshowings of an as yet un-announced product.andP;  Wes Thomas, representingTimeWorks, told Newsbytes: &quot; We felt it was important to receive input fromknowledgeable people concerning our new product which we expect to release in4th quarter and this setting provided a suitable environment for thisactivity.andP;  We also have a booth inside MacWorld showing our existing productsand the trailer is limited to the new product.&quot; Those visiting the trailer tolook at the new product were bound by non-disclosure agreements not todivulge information on the system.andP;  Timeworks present product line crossesthe Macintosh, IBM-PC, Commodore and Apple II platforms and includes theWordWiter and Beyond WordWriter word processing systems and the PublishIt!andO;series of desktop publishing programs.andM;(Barbara E. McMullen andamp; John F. McMullen/19900809/Press Contacts: Eric Gould,International Business Software, 408-522-8000; Wes Thomas, TimeWorks,516-266-1652)</TEXT></DOC>